The Decimal System
The decimal system (from Medieval Latin decimalis, derived from Latin decem 'ten') is a mathematical concept for the numeral system that has established itself as the international standard today. In its structure, it is a positional numeral system with base ten, utilizing ten distinct digits. The numerical symbols are formed from the decimal digits 0 to 9 and their positional combinations. In this form, the decimal system is applicable to integers and—when supplemented by a decimal separator—to non-integers. It is also referred to as the base-10 system or decadic system. In older publications, the term denary system can also be found.
Historically, these decimal numbers developed within Indian numeral script. They reached European countries via the Arab world. In German-speaking regions, the decimal system dominates all numerical thinking and writing. Aside from it, the binary system (dual system) and the hexadecimal system (sedecimal system) occupy niche roles, primarily in computer science and digital data processing.
In the numeral scripts of traditional Chinese and Japanese decimal systems, there are additional characters for powers of ten alongside the digits for natural numbers from 1 to 9. The latter are combined pairwise with a numeral digit. This notation is increasingly being replaced by Indian numerals.
In the early stages of numeral systems and scripts, base ten was frequently chosen. The simple explanation for this preference lies in the fact that "our first personal computer" is our ten fingers, which serve as counting and calculating tools in finger arithmetic.
Proposals emerging since the 19th century to introduce the duodecimal system (base-12) instead of the decimal system due to its structural advantages have remained unsuccessful to date.
Mathematical Operations (Verknüpfungen)
In mathematics, an operation (or binary operation / composition) is used as an umbrella term for various mathematical procedures: In addition to basic arithmetic (addition, subtraction, etc., yielding sums or differences), it encompasses geometric operations (such as reflection, rotation) as well as logical operators. The term is also used to denote the composition (chaining) of functions. In general, an operation defines how mathematical objects of the same or similar type determine a further object together.
For a relatively small set of elements and an operation with few arity (such as two operands), this definition can be clearly presented using an operation table (Cayley table), listing all possible pairs and their respective results.
The Equals Sign
The equals sign ($=$) stands in mathematics, formal logic, and exact natural sciences between two expressions of equal value.
Basic Arithmetic Operations
The four basic arithmetic operations are addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division. Mastering these operations belongs to the core skills of reading, writing, and arithmetic taught in school education.
In arithmetic, addition and multiplication are viewed as primary operations, while subtraction and division are considered derived operations. For the two primary operations, fundamental rules apply (commutative, associative, and distributive laws). In algebra, these concepts are abstracted to transfer them to other mathematical structures.
Addition
Addition is the process of summing two or more numbers. The operator is the plus sign $+$, the operands are called addends, the expression is a sum, and the result is the value of the sum:
$$\text{Addend} + \text{Addend} = \text{Sum Value}$$
Adding natural numbers always yields a natural number.
Subtraction
Subtraction is the process of taking one number away from another. The operator is the minus sign $-$, the operands are called minuend and subtrahend, the expression is the difference, and the result is the value of the difference:
$$\text{Minuend} - \text{Subtrahend} = \text{Difference Value}$$
Subtracting two natural numbers yields a natural number only if the minuend is greater than the subtrahend. If equal, the result is zero ($0$). If the subtrahend is larger, a negative integer results. Thus, the number domain is extended to integers.
Multiplication
Multiplication is the process of multiplying two or more numbers. The operator is the multiplication sign $\cdot$ or $\times$ (or $*$); the operands are called multiplicand and multiplier (or collectively factors), the expression is a product, and the result is the product value:
$$\text{Multiplier} \cdot \text{Multiplicand} = \text{Product Value}$$
For natural numbers $m$ and $n$:
$$m \cdot n = \underbrace{n + n + \dots + n}_{m \text{ times}} = k$$
Division
Division is the process of dividing one number by another. The operator is the division sign $:$ or $/$ (or $\div$), the operands are called dividend and divisor, the expression is a quotient, and the result is the quotient value:
$$\text{Dividend} : \text{Divisor} = \text{Quotient Value}$$
Division by zero ($0$) cannot be meaningfully defined.
Calculation Rules & Algebraic Structures
For numbers $a$, $b$, and $c$:
Commutative Laws:
$$a + b = b + a \quad \text{and} \quad a \cdot b = b \cdot a$$
Associative Laws:
$$(a + b) + c = a + (b + c) \quad \text{and} \quad (a \cdot b) \cdot c = a \cdot (b \cdot c)$$
Distributive Laws:
$$a \cdot (b + c) = a \cdot b + a \cdot c \quad \text{and} \quad (a + b) \cdot c = a \cdot c + b \cdot c$$
Identity Elements:
$$a + 0 = a \quad \text{and} \quad a \cdot 1 = a$$
Algebraic Structures:
$(\mathbb{N}, +)$: Commutative semigroup.
$(\mathbb{N}, \cdot)$: Commutative semigroup.
$(\mathbb{Z}, +)$: Commutative group (with identity and inverse elements).
$(\mathbb{Z}, +, \cdot)$: Commutative ring.
$(\mathbb{Q}, +, \cdot)$: Field.
Physical Concepts: Time, Length, Mass, Force
Time
Time, along with space, is one of the fundamental concepts used to organize perceptions of events and processes. In physics, time is represented by the variable $t$ and its SI unit is the second ($\mathrm{s}$).
Length
Length describes the spatial dimension of physical objects in a direction and the distance between them. Symbol: $l$ (or $s$ for path distance), SI unit: meter ($\mathrm{m}$).
Mass
Mass is an intrinsic property of matter determining inertia and gravitational attraction (Equivalence Principle). Symbol: $m$, SI unit: kilogram ($\mathrm{kg}$).
