**Time**, along with space, belongs to the general basic concepts used to capture and order perceptions of events and processes. With the help of time, all events in the universe can be divided into past, present, and future. The present consists of all events that are simultaneous with the "now". Time describes the progression of the present coming from the past and leading to the future. It has a clear, irreversible direction. In the case of two events, one of which causes or even merely influences the other, the cause occurs earlier than the effect (principle of causality). With the help of the physical principles of thermodynamics, the direction of time can be determined by the increase in entropy, i.e., roughly the disorder in a closed system.

Time and space exist in everyday consciousness and in classical physics as given and independent of each other. This concept proves itself in the realm of everyday processes. However, it contradicts the fact that the speed of a light beam in a vacuum is a constant of nature, which depends neither on whether the light source is moving nor on the direction in which the light beam is moving. Moreover, no body, no signal, and no other physical influence can get from one place to another faster than light in a vacuum. This is the starting point of the theory of relativity.

A consequence of this is that events at different locations that happen simultaneously for one observer are not simultaneous for a second observer moving relative to the first. There is therefore no universal "now". Furthermore, time passes at different speeds for all observers who are moving relative to each other or who are located in places with different gravitational potentials. Only observers who are at rest relative to each other can have exactly the same time. However, the corrections necessary according to the theory of relativity are of negligible magnitude in everyday processes and are only noticeable with the highest measurement accuracy, such as in meter-accurate positioning using GPS.

To specify a point in time precisely, the time span after or before a special event selected by convention (e.g., "Birth of Christ" or "Midnight") is used. For this purpose, the calendar date and time are used in accordance with legally agreed regulations. As a physical quantity, time usually has the formula symbol $t$ (from Lat. *tempus* for "time"), its SI unit is the second $s$.

For the physical, bio-, and human sciences, and for technology, time is a central parameter that can also be measured metrologically, especially in all types of motion (e.g., in kinematics) and other processes of change. In philosophy, the nature of time has always been questioned, which also touches on issues of worldview. Psychology investigates time perception and the sense of time. Economics also views time as an object of value.

