Length measurement is carried out by comparing the length to be measured with standards of known length. Two lengths are considered equal if their start and end points can be brought into respective coincidence simultaneously. The length of a standard is considered constant in classical physics. In special relativity, however, length depends on the relative state of motion between the measured object and the standard. From the perspective of the measuring observer, one speaks of relativistic length contraction.

